12.1 Introduction

In Chapter 10, we developed a mathematical and visual framework in order to assess and design for intended steady-state error behaviour for a range of expected reference signals. We then considered transient closed-loop design specifications on the complementary sensitivity function magnitude in Chapter 11, and were able to repose these specifications in the log-polar plane, where assessment of indicates adherence to the prescribed specifications. However, we have not yet outlined a methodical design procedure in order to shape such that it meets the generated frequency domain boundaries. We will now consider this crucial final step of the analysis and design process, starting from the simplest of feedback controllers, to more complex and involved controllers.

In other words, at high frequencies, the noise signal makes its way to the plant input based on the high-frequency gain of . Because we do not want high-frequency noise to act on our system, we therefore should design to be as small as possible. 12.2.3 Designing for margins of stability

Recall that when using a log-polar plot, the gain margin corresponds with the amount of gain required to raise the curve such that it passes through the critical point, which occurs at the phase crossover frequency . The phase margin (in degrees) corresponds to the amount of phase required to shift the curve leftwards such that it passes through the critical point, which occurs at the gain crossover frequency . This is illustrated in Figure 12.4.
Figure 12.4: Visualisation of gain and phase margin on log-polar plot.
If the desired gain and phase margins are marked on the log-polar plot, then we can adjust K to attempt to meet the required margins of stability. Based on the limitations of , we can only shift the locus up and down, but depending on the structure of it may be possible to adjust the gain of via K in order to adhere to the gain and phase margins.

Example

Using a log-polar plot, design a proportional feedback controller that provides a phase margin of , and gain margin of dB, for the open-loop plant .
We begin by marking our log-polar plot for the gain and phase margin requirements. For the phase margin, we need to have a phase angle greater than at the gain crossover frequency, so we make a mark at the coordinate , with the requirement that passes to the right of this mark. For the gain margin, we need to be at least 6 dB below the critical point when at the phase crossover frequency, so we make a mark at the coordinate , with the requirement that the locus passes below this mark.
The code below generates the log-polar plot of , and also includes the markers for the gain and phase margins.
clear
s = tf('s');
 
P = 10/s/(1+s/5)/(1+s/5);
 
K = 1;
L = K*P;
 
[magL,phiL] = nichols(L,{1e-3,1e3});
 
figure, hold on
plot(squeeze(phiL),squeeze(20*log10(magL)))
plot(-135,0,'r>',MarkerFaceColor='red') %phase margin marker
plot(-180,-6,'rv',MarkerFaceColor='red') %gain margin marker
plot(-180,0,'or',MarkerSize=5,MarkerFaceColor='r')
legend('$L(j\omega)$','interpreter','latex','Location','southeast')
Using the code above, when , we are not meeting the gain and phase margins. In fact, our closed-loop system will be unstable for , as is intercepting the critical point. We therefore need to reduce the gain of by using . After some experimenting, we can show that for we can meet both the gain and phase margin requirements. Note that we have ended up with a gain margin greater than our specification, as a result of only have a single degree of freedom in our feedback controller (only a single parameter can be varied). We could increase the order of to reduce the overdesign, but this will be covered later in the chapter.
Note that there does not necessarily exist a value that simultaneously satisfies both the gain and phase margin requirements. If this is the case, then we should consider using a higher order controller, such as a lead controller (see Section 12.4).

12.2.5 Designing for transient design specifications

Chapter 11 introduced a methodology for representing design requirements on , which can be visualised in a log-polar plot. We can now use our understanding of shifting the upwards/downwards using K in order to try satisfy the prescribed design specifications for a particular plant. However, before commencing with the design of , we should be wary of the limitations of using a proportional controller:
  • Zero steady-state error — because is Type-0, , which we have no control over, would have to be the correct type number in order to ensure the required reference to output tracking. Additionally, Type-0 means that plant input disturbances will never be rejected completely at steady-state. So if zero steady-state error to step-like disturbances is a system requirement, then a proportional controller is not a viable solution.
  • Transient design specifications — depending on the structure of , a proportional controller will not necessarily be able to meet the prescribed transient design specifications. In other words, shifting the up/down in a log-polar plot may not provide the sufficient design degrees of freedom to meet the stay-out constraints on the loop transfer function. This would be another example where is not a viable control solution. Notably, we often will not know whether will be a viable solution for the prescribed transient design specifications until we try!
Assuming the aforementioned issues are not present, we can proceed with the proportional control design.

The only way for to exit the stay-out region (indicated with blue dotted lines) is to reduce the gain of sufficiently using . For , both tracking constraints can be adhered to.
At this point we could stop, but what we should also notice is that we can reduce the gain of K further whilst still meeting both tracking requirements. As discussed earlier in the Chapter, we want to minimise the high-frequency gain of , which for the proportional controller is given by K. This is also beneficial, as reduced gain in the feedback controller results in a smaller control action, based on , which means that our closed-loop system will be "cheaper" in terms of energy consumption and component wear.
For a gain of we can just meet the bandwidth requirement, whilst simultaneously easily meeting the overshoot constraint. We should therefore expect to closely adhere to the settling time requirement (as is now sitting right on the boundary condition for the bandwidth specification) whilst having overshoot substantially less than the worst-case allowance (as is now relatively far from the stay-out region originating from the overshoot specification). 12.3 Proportional-plus-integral controller design

A proportional-plus-integral (PI) controller is required in the following cases:
  1. The type number of needs be increased by one to meet steady-state requirements with respect to reference signals. For example, if is Type-0 and we require zero-error step reference tracking at steady-state, then needs to be Type-1 to make Type-1.
  2. needs to be Type-1 to meet steady-state requirements with respect to plant input disturbances. Aside from the case above, this is required when there are plant input disturbances acting on the system and the user specifications requires that the disturbances be completely rejected at steady-state.
If neither of the above conditions apply, then we need not design an integral controller.

12.3.1 Definition

The PI controller is given by

12.3.3 Design methodology

Owing to the fact that a PI controller resembles that of a P controller of the form at sufficiently high frequencies (), we can begin by designing our controller under the assumption that it is simply a proportional controller. One way of doing this is to initially set the integral time constant, , to a sufficiently large number, thereby making the zero frequency, , very low. We can then design in the same manner as previously in order to meet the required stability and/or transient tracking requirements. Once we have met those requirements, we can then begin to decrease . Importantly, we still need to be sufficiently small, otherwise the integral action will take a very long time to reduce the tracking error to zero. On the other hand, very small values results in increased phase lag across a wider frequency range, which makes satisfying stability conditions more tricky. We therefore want a small enough value that also does not interfere with the tracking and stability design specifications.
As briefly discussed in Chapter 11, we will treat the stay-above boundary differently for Type-1+ systems. So far, we have only discussed Type-0 systems. In order to ensure that approaches unity, we shall adjust our stay-above bandwidth constraint from before such that the lower bound represents for the desired frequency bandwidth. In order to not be too overly constraining on the closed-loop gain, we use a lower bound magnitude of (or approximately dB) instead of , with a frequency range of , where is the peak frequency of a second-order system, which we previously defined as
.

Note that the choice of is largely heuristic — we can choose a range of values sufficiently close to (but also sufficiently less than) unity.

12.4 Proportional-plus-derivative controller design

A proportional-plus-derivative (PD), often also referred to as a lead controller, is required when a proportional controller is not able to meet the required margins of stability (e.g. gain and phase margins), or transient design specifications (e.g. overshoot and bandwidth requirements). Specifically, when the loop transfer function requires additional phase lead. Note that our previous considerations of P and PI controllers never contribute phase lead. Instead, they either contribute no phase lead/lag (in the case of the P controller), and only phase lag (in the case of the PI controller).
As we will show in the following sections, a PD controller is able to provide phase lead at key design frequencies, at the cost of increasing the high-frequency gain of . This type of controller therefore makes a trade-off between stability/performance and noise sensitivity.

12.5 Proportional-integral-derivative controller design

A proportional-integral-derivative (PID) controller is necessary when both phase lead is required (e.g. to meet stability margins), as well as integral action (e.g. to fully reject disturbances at steady state). Analogous to how a PI controller behaves like a P controller at the mid to high frequencies, a PID controller behaves like a PD controller at these frequencies. We can use this relationship to design our PID controller in a procedural way.

12.5.1 Definition

The PID controller is given by
,
where α and β is the zero and pole of from the PD component, respectively, is integral time constant, andK is a gain applied at all frequencies. In simple terms, the PID controller can be thought of as a combination of a PD and PI controller.

12.5.2 Frequency response

The frequency response of a PID controller is determined as
.
The magnitude response can be found as
,
with a corresponding phase response of
.

12.5.3 Design methodology

Recall that a PI controller is designed based on first setting and then choosing K based on the fact that the PI controller behaves like a P controller under this condition. Once K is chosen, is then reduced until the frequency response locus approaches the stability bounds. Analogous to this, we can design a PID controller as follows, by first designing it as if its a PD controller, followed by adjusting the integral time:
  • Step 1: Set , which implies that , which resembles a PD controller.
  • Step 2: Set K equal to a value such that the design frequency point sits nears the critical point so that the amount of phase lead required at mid frequencies can be easily inferred.
  • Step 3: Select based on design methodology detailed in Section 12.4.3.
  • Step 4: After selecting the set that meets design requirements, continually reduce value until stability design boundaries are close to limit (with some minor safety margin).
Importantly, we will use the stay-above formulation for a Type-1+ controller, as we are still contributing an integrator as part of our PID controller.
